    <h3>Retrospective</h3>

    <h4>More customer interactions and user research, and even in-house research</h4>

    <p>There is only so much time in the day, but I always wish there was more time in the day for customer feedback and user research. We have performed light weight guerrilla research at Starbucks coffee shops and remote usability sessions, and even in person design workshops with some of our current customers. I’m always in awe at the gold mine of information and clarity these sessions bring. Elementum doesn’t have a full time User Researcher, <em>but we are currently looking for one</em>. I can only imagine the amount of useful testing results and findings a full time research can bring to the design team.</p>

    <h4>More in depth analytics</h4>

    <p>Analytics wasn’t a huge priority when Transport was first built. Over the past year there has been a big push for placing the right hooks and identifying the funnels for analytic tracking. The insights we have gathered from what data we are capturing now are so insightful. And can be both encouraging to see the usage and helpful when deciding what to prioritize for the next set of features.</p>

    <h4>Be flexible with your tools</h4>

    <p>Ever since the start of the project I have been experimenting with multiple prototyping tools. <%= link_to "I wrote about it on my blog here", "http://writing.enchant.co/2014/11/28/top-prototyping-tools-for-interaction-designers/" %>. I’ve also been balancing my documentation between the collaborative Google docs or the well organized Confluence. I’m always striving for the same thing, get everyone on the same page and keep the process well documented and up to date. </p>

    <p>As an interaction design that means using the visual medium to communicate ideas like flows or wireframes or prototypes, and it doesn’t matter what tool you use to get the job done. Just as long as you are able to produce design documentation that aids clarification and helps the team move forward.</p>
